Question	One-Line Answer
What is DDL?	DDL (Data Definition Language) is used to create, modify, and delete database structures.
CREATE	Creates a new database object such as a database or table.
ALTER	Modifies the structure of an existing table.
DROP	Permanently deletes a database object and all its data.
TRUNCATE	Removes all rows from a table while keeping its structure.
DROP vs TRUNCATE	DROP removes the table itself; TRUNCATE removes only the data.
NOT NULL	Prevents a column from storing NULL values.
UNIQUE	Ensures all values in a column are distinct.
CHECK	Allows only values that satisfy a specified condition.
DEFAULT	Automatically inserts a predefined value when none is provided.


